bib_record.title: Resonance parameters of Tantalum-181 in neutron energy range from 100 to 4300 eV

free_txt: Y.Kanda
Main reference.
Prelim. data in short note
Electron LINAC at JAERI. Electron
Energy 120 MeV. Burst width 30 ns. Repetition Rate
300 Hz. Average beam current 20 - 30 microAmps.
The transmission data were analyzed according to the
multi-level Breit-Wigner formula combined with least-
squares fitting program SIOB taking into account
level-level interference, Doppler broadening and
instrumental resolution effects.
The capture width was assumed to have a constant value
of 55 meV for all levels.
Neutron energy was calibrated using the well determined
sharp resonances of Pb-209 and S-32.
All observed resonances were assumed to be excited by
s-wave neutrons. g was taken from REL-REF BNL-325, if
available, otherwise g=0.5 was used.
The transmission data were corrected for dead time and
for background, the latter by using the black resonan-
ces of Na-23 and U-238,also black resonances of Ta-181
A 11.1 cm diameter by 0.635 cm thick Li-6 glass
scintillator was used in the low resolution measure-
ments.
In the high resolution measurements, five sets of Li-6
glass detectors, 11.1 cm in diameter and 1.25 cm
thick, were used.
Neutron intensities were monitored with two Li-6 glass
detectors set at the 45 and 100 m stations.
Electron LINAC at JAERI. Electron
Energy 120 MeV. Burst width 30 ns. Repetition Rate
300 Hz. Average beam current 20 - 30 microAmps.
Laminated water cooled tantalum target. Neutron
beam moderated by a boron loaded polythene disk, 20 cm
in diameter and 5 cm thick. Gamma-rays from the target
were blocked by a 30 cm thick lead shadow ring. A 5 mm
thick boron nitride plate or a 6 cm thick boric plate
was placed in the neutron beam to remove time overlap
slow neutrons for the low and high resolution measure-
ments, respectively.
time of flight techniques used, with evacuated
flight path lengths of 56.34 or 191.52 m for low and
high resolution measurements, respectively.
Transmission measurements.
Details of experimental
procedure.
Neutron cross
sections, BNL-325, 3rd edition, v.1, Resonance
Parameters. -Reference for ASSUM.
All samples were 10.2 cm square metallic plates of
natural tantalum. The chemical purity was more than
99.99 %, while the isotopic purity of Ta-181 was
99.988 % . Two samples with thicknesses 0.00565 and
0.0560 atoms/barn, and tree samples of 0.0112, 0.0280
and 0.0560 atoms/barn were used for the low and high
resolution measurements, respectively.
The samples were placed at distances of 51 or 100 m
from the neutron producing target for the two measure-
ments, respectively.
For background determination - 5 mm thick metallic
sodium in low resolution measurement, 15 mm thick
natural uranium plate in high resolution measurement.
Parameters below 510 eV were determined by low
resolution measurement, above 510 eV by high resolution
measurement.
From REL-REF BNL-325.
Total errors, dominated by statistical
errors.
Table 2 from Nucl.Sci.Tech.,24(1987)975
For statistical analysis the resonance parameters
below 100 eV were taken from REL-REF BNL-325.
It was assumed, that the contributions of the p-wave
resonances were negligible and almost all the observed
resonances below a few keV are s-wave.
Neutron strength function values were defined from
slope of curve, Fig.5 of main reference,- cumulative
plot of reduced neutron widths.
The error was estimated from conventional
statistical assumption deltaS0/S0=(2/N)**1/2, where N
is the number of levels.
Table 3 and text,p.986 from
Nucl.Sci.Tech.17(1978)43
For statistical analysis the resonance parameters
below 100 eV were taken from REL-REF BNL-325.
It was assumed, that the contributions of the p-wave
resonances were negligible and almost all the observed
resonances below a few keV are s-wave.
From curve of cumulative count of levels versus
neutron energy below 1700 eV (Fig.4 of main reference)
the value of average level spacing of 4.77 eV was
deduced. Final value was deduced using in analysis the
Porter-Thomas distributions and corrections for
missing levels.
